                <div type="title" xml:lang="en">
                    <head>
                        <lb/>Embleme 12. Of the Secrets of Nature.
                        <lb/>The Stone, which Saturne vomited up, being devoured instead
                        <lb/>of his sonne jupiter, is placed in Helicon as a monument to men.
                    </head>
                </div>
                
                
                <div type="epigram" xml:lang="en">
                    <head>Epigramme 12.</head>
                    <lg>
                        <l>Know would you why the poets soe recount</l>
                        <l>The fame of Helicon, the Muses mount?</l>
                        <l>That monumentall stone is plac'd thereon,</l>
                        <l>Which Saturne gorg'd instead of Jove his sonne.</l>
                        <l>Be wise, the sense agrees not wish the sound,</l>
                        <l>For Saturn's stone in Chymistrys found.</l>
                    </lg>
                </div>
                
                
                <pb n="42"/> <!-- Change to page number of the actual manuscript -->
                <div type="discourse" xml:lang="en">
                    <head>Discourse 12.</head>
                    <ab><!--Our convention will be that if we have break = "no" then it means that the word is broken across the line with a dash--> 
                        <lb/>The Allegory of Saturne wee find to be taken divers wayes: for the Astro<milestone unit="section" n="e03-01" /> <!-- Change the value of n to "e" plus the number of the emblem (in two digits), followed by a hyphen and then a two-digit count of sentence -->
                        <lb break="no"/>nomers repute him the highest of the planetts in order; the young students
                        <lb/>of Chymistry the meanest of metalls, namely lead: The heathen poets: con
                        <lb break="no"/>ceivd him to be the father of Jupiter, sonne of Caelum; the Mythologists time.
                        <lb/>But though all these may seem to have thought aright in their sense, yet
                        <lb/>they will not declare those things which are elswhere spoken of Saturne,
                        <lb/>why hee devoured and vomited up his sonns, and a stone instead of Jupiter,
                        why hee is the discoverer of truth, why appearing with a sieth
                        
                        
                        
                        <pb n="16"/><fw>Discourse 3.</fw><!-- Page number of the actual manuscript, followed by the header on the page. -->
                        
                    </ab>   
                </div>
                
